<header>
    <h1>Chapter 1 : Description of Data</h1>
    <p>Fundamentals of Probability and Statistics</p>
</header>

<div class="container">

<h2>1. Introduction</h2>
<p>Data is a collection of numerical or qualitative information collected for a specific purpose. Statistics helps us organize, analyze, and interpret data to make correct decisions.</p>

<h2>2. Types of Variables</h2>
<ul>
<li><b>Qualitative Variables:</b> Non-numerical values such as gender, color, and category.</li>
<li><b>Quantitative Variables:</b> Numerical values such as height, age, marks, and income.</li>
</ul>

<h2>3. Measures of Central Tendency</h2>

<p>Measures of central tendency describe the center of the data and include mean, median, and mode.</p>

<h2>4. Measures of Dispersion</h2>

<p>Measures of dispersion explain how the data values are spread around the center. Important measures include variance, standard deviation, coefficient of variation, and skewness.</p>

<h2>5. Graphical Representation of Data</h2>
<ul>
<li>Histogram</li>
<li>Frequency Curve</li>
<li>Ogive</li>
<li>Box Plot</li>
</ul>

<h2>6. Solved Problems</h2>

<h3>Problem 1: Mean, Median and Mode</h3>
<div class="solution">
<b>Find the mean, median and mode of the data:</b><br>
4, 6, 8, 10, 12, 14, 14, 15

<br><br>
<b>Step 1: Arrange the data</b><br>
4, 6, 8, 10, 12, 14, 14, 15

<br><br>
<b>Step 2: Find Mean</b><br>
Sum = 4 + 6 + 8 + 10 + 12 + 14 + 14 + 15 = 83<br>
Number of observations = 8<br>
Mean = 83 / 8 = <b>10.375</b>

<br><br>
<b>Step 3: Find Median</b><br>
Since n = 8 (even), Median = average of 4th and 5th terms<br>
= (10 + 12) / 2 = <b>11</b>

<br><br>
<b>Step 4: Find Mode</b><br>
14 occurs most frequently → <b>Mode = 14</b>
</div>

<h3>Problem 2: Variance and Standard Deviation</h3>
<div class="solution">
<b>Find the variance and standard deviation of the data:</b><br>
5, 7, 9, 11, 13

<br><br>
<b>Step 1: Find Mean</b><br>
Mean = (5 + 7 + 9 + 11 + 13) / 5 = 45 / 5 = <b>9</b>

<br><br>
<b>Step 2: Find deviations from mean</b><br>
5−9 = −4 → (−4)² = 16<br>
7−9 = −2 → 4<br>
9−9 = 0 → 0<br>
11−9 = 2 → 4<br>
13−9 = 4 → 16

<br><br>
<b>Step 3: Find Variance</b><br>
Variance = (16 + 4 + 0 + 4 + 16) / 5 = 40 / 5 = <b>8</b>

<br><br>
<b>Step 4: Find Standard Deviation</b><br>
Standard Deviation = √8 = <b>2.828</b>
<h3>Problem 3: Combined Mean</h3>
<div class="solution">
<b>Given:</b><br>
Group A: 20 students, mean = 45<br>
Group B: 30 students, mean = 55

<br><br>
<b>Step 1: Formula for Combined Mean</b><br>
Combined Mean = (n₁x̄₁ + n₂x̄₂) / (n₁ + n₂)

<br><br>
<b>Step 2: Substitution</b><br>
= (20×45 + 30×55) / (20 + 30)<br>
= (900 + 1650) / 50<br>
= 2550 / 50 = <b>51</b>

<br><br>
<b>Answer:</b> Combined Mean = <b>51</b>
</div>

<h3>Problem 4: Mean Using Step Deviation Method</h3>
<div class="solution">
<b>Find the mean of:</b><br>
10, 20, 30, 40, 50

<br><br>
<b>Step 1:</b> Take assumed mean A = 30

<br><br>
<b>Step 2:</b> Find deviations (d = x − A):<br>
10−30 = −20<br>
20−30 = −10<br>
30−30 = 0<br>
40−30 = 10<br>
50−30 = 20

<br><br>
<b>Step 3:</b> Find Σd = −20 − 10 + 0 + 10 + 20 = 0

<br><br>
<b>Step 4:</b> Mean = A + (Σd / n)<br>
= 30 + (0 / 5) = <b>30</b>
</div>

<h3>Problem 5: Finding Median from Discrete Frequency Distribution</h3>
<div class="solution">
<b>Marks:</b> 10, 20, 30, 40, 50<br>
<b>Frequency:</b> 3, 7, 12, 5, 3

<br><br>
<b>Step 1:</b> Find total frequency N<br>
N = 3 + 7 + 12 + 5 + 3 = 30

<br><br>
<b>Step 2:</b> Find cumulative frequency

<table border="1" cellpadding="6">
<tr><th>Marks</th><th>f</th><th>cf</th></tr>
<tr><td>10</td><td>3</td><td>3</td></tr>
<tr><td>20</td><td>7</td><td>10</td></tr>
<tr><td>30</td><td>12</td><td>22</td></tr>
<tr><td>40</td><td>5</td><td>27</td></tr>
<tr><td>50</td><td>3</td><td>30</td></tr>
</table>

<br><br>
<b>Step 3:</b> Find N/2 = 30/2 = 15  
The cumulative frequency just greater than 15 is 22

<br><br>
<b>Answer:</b> Median = <b>30</b>
<h3> Histogram </h3>

<div class="solution">
<b>Given Data:</b>

<table border="1" cellpadding="6">
<tr><th>Class Interval</th><th>Frequency</th></tr>
<tr><td>0–10</td><td>4</td></tr>
<tr><td>10–20</td><td>7</td></tr>
<tr><td>20–30</td><td>12</td></tr>
<tr><td>30–40</td><td>5</td></tr>
</table>

<br>
<b>Step 1:</b> Draw X-axis and Y-axis  
<br>
<b>Step 2:</b> Mark class intervals on X-axis  
<br>
<b>Step 3:</b> Mark frequencies on Y-axis  
<br>
<b>Step 4:</b> Draw rectangles of equal width for each class

<br><br>

Maximum frequency occurs in class 20–30.
</div>

